            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this lye calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool uses standard SAP (saponification) values to calculate
                how much sodium hydroxide (NaOH) or potassium hydroxide (KOH)
                you need to fully saponify the oils in your recipe, then applies
                your chosen superfat and water settings.
              </p>

              <h3>1. SAP values and basic formula</h3>
              <p>
                Each oil has a SAP value: the amount of lye needed to turn
                1&nbsp;gram of that oil into soap. For NaOH, SAP values are
                typically around 0.13–0.19&nbsp;g NaOH per gram of oil.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Theoretical lye (no superfat):</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Lye}_{\text{theoretical}} = \sum (\text{Oil weight}_i
                  \times \text{SAP}_i) \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Step 2 – Apply superfat:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Lye}_{\text{actual}} =
                  \text{Lye}_{\text{theoretical}} \times (1 -
                  \text{Superfat}/100) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                For KOH, SAP values are higher. Many references multiply NaOH
                SAP by about 1.403 to get the KOH equivalent. This calculator
                stores both NaOH and KOH SAP values for common oils.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Water calculation</h3>
              <p>You can choose between two common approaches:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Water : lye ratio</strong> – e.g. 2.5:1 means: \[
                  \text{Water} = \text{Lye}_{\text{actual}} \times 2.5 \]
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Lye concentration</strong> – percentage of lye in the
                  lye solution: \[ \text{Lye concentration} =
                  \frac{\text{Lye}}{\text{Water} + \text{Lye}} \times 100 \]
                  Rearranged to find water: \[ \text{Water} = \text{Lye} \times
                  \left(\frac{100}{C} - 1\right) \] where \(C\) is the lye
                  concentration in %.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Working by oil weights vs. batch size</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Oil weights mode</strong> – you directly enter the
                  weight of each oil. The calculator sums them and computes lye
                  and water.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Batch size mode</strong> – you enter the total oil
                  weight and percentages for each oil. The calculator converts
                  percentages to weights, then proceeds as above.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Typical SAP values for common soap oils</h2>
              <p>
